article.description: After Chelsea Newton made a free throw with 2:29 left to break a 54-all tie, Cappie Pondexter scored seven straight points and No. 10 Rutgers held off Syracuse 64-54 on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Pondexter dominates in clutch for Rutgers
article.linkText: Pondexter pushes No. 10 Rutgers past Syracuse
article.story:
SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Cappie Pondexter saved her best for the
final minutes.

After Chelsea Newton made a free throw with 2:29 left to break a
54-all tie, Pondexter scored seven straight points and No. 10
Rutgers held off Syracuse 64-54 on Wednesday night.

Playing with four fouls, Pondexter hit a layup high off the
glass, drained a 3-pointer from the top of the key, and made a pair
of free throws in a span of just over a minute to stretch the lead
to 62-54 and finish the Orange (11-13, 3-10 Big East).
	   
"They were uncontested shots,'' said Pondexter, who finished
with 25 points. "They left me wide open, so I took the shot.''
	   
It was the fourth straight victory for Rutgers (19-5, 10-2) and
the fifth straight loss for Syracuse, which dropped its 15th
straight game to a ranked team.

"Cappie is a pressure player. She can handle that,'' Rutgers
coach C. Vivian Stringer said. "She's steady throughout. When it
comes to crunch time, she'll make the better decision.''

Freshman star Matee Ajavon struggled to score 12 points on
5-of-14 shooting and committed a season-high 10 turnovers, and
Rebecca Richman had eight points and 10 rebounds for the Scarlet
Knights, who beat Syracuse 69-61 just 10 days ago.

Jessica Richter had 21 points and Tracy Harbut 11, career highs
for both, to lead the Orange.

Rutgers was coming off a 76-62 win over No. 11 Connecticut on
Sunday, but Syracuse battled the Scarlet Knights hard throughout.

Richter hit a 3-pointer from the top of the key to give Syracuse
the first basket of the game, and although the Orange trailed by as
many as seven in the first half they rallied to 31-all at halftime.

Syracuse finally gained a 35-33 lead on two free throws by
Richter at 17:23 of the second half, and Chineze Nwagbo converted a
layup after a steal by Mary Joe Riley to give the Orange a 46-42
edge midway through the period.

Consecutive layups by Ajavon evened the score at 48 with 8:21
left, the fourth tie of the half, and the lead changed two more
times in the next five minutes.

"We played our hearts out, I'm just real proud of the effort,''
Syracuse coach Keith Cieplicki said. "We had some breakdowns at
the end.''

After Richter's driving layup tied the game for the last time
with 3 minutes to go, the Orange did not score again. Syracuse
scored just four baskets and did not take a free throw over the
final 10 minutes.

"We didn't finish the game,'' said Rochelle Coleman, who had
seven points and four steals for Syracuse. "We were in it the
whole game, but at the end when we really needed it we were
lacking.''

A furious attempt to rally one last time fizzled. Richter missed
a baseline runner and a 3-point attempt, and Lauren Kohn failed on
a long 3.

The first half turned into a duel between Pondexter and Richter,
who each scored 14 points.

Rutgers went up by seven in the first seven minutes, and
Pondexter's turnaround jumper in the lane kept the Scarlet Knights
ahead 23-16 with 7:26 left.

Richter then led the Orange back, scoring seven points over the
final six minutes. She converted a rebound basket and hit a
3-pointer from the left corner on consecutive possessions to move
Syracuse within 25-23 with 4:50 remaining. She then hit two free
throws in the final minute to tie the game at the break.
